At the end of the exchange, the Prague stock exchange fluctuated in the negative
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the trade, the Prague stock exchange resumed with its fall from the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan of the US financial sector, is thus also noticeable in our country.
The fall of actions in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even though the indices managed, during the day, to wipe out some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng index lost four percent during trading, but later it wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five per cent, but ultimately managed to reduce losses to 4.3 per cent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“The hesitation about the rescue action in the US will affect financial markets around the world,” notes Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its own monetary policy, i.e. independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will suffer from this.
The Bloodbath of American Actions
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the draft support for the financial system, which it was expected to devote up to $700 billion (nearly CZK 12 trillion).
The lawmakers thus denied the call for support for President George Bush’s project.
According to Bush, the project is expected to address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday and major stock indices experienced the biggest drop in the past 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a drop of this magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress ceded: U.S. government could inject $700 billion into banks
U.S. Congress leaders and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial aid agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turn in the talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial aid of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns), granted to the U.S. financial system.
But success is not so sure.
Indeed, before being able to publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulatory Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout plan will be adopted should be a major psychological factor in curbing financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which aid to markets can be effective, there will be a "disillusion".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent opinions on the form the package of measures should have for stabilizing the market," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be held on Sunday.
On Saturday night, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the government a final form.
It should buy back from financial companies unsold real estate assets that cause financial firms to suffer considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are on the verge of agreeing on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still need to pursue this plan of market recovery, but I think we are there,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the declining stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, the lawmakers are making sure that Congress comes to a final agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress’ decision could affect Monday’s trade.
But for the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will proceed to vote, or if negotiations are not likely to be blocked, at the last moment, by one or another problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, there will still be many changes in the law.
The total amount allocated to the system shall be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, should be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not performing its function, it has the option of blocking the grant of the remaining amount, in two steps: first, an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomes progress in the negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, the Congress, he, has the opportunity to put it in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which consisted in obtaining funds for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed Sunday with the vote of the law, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President George W. Bush is pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of Golden Parachute
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said lawmakers agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the settlement agreement, the progress of the time-based plan.
The new law also provides for limiting the so-called gold parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and will be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for real estate owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new installments in the case of mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological aid
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
“And this is due to the fact that we do not know what the mechanism and price of buying back troubled assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told the iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, according to Marek, is not as important as that.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree, as of this week, that they support this plan and that they will dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, anticipating the adoption of the plan, matters the most at the moment," said Marek.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While virtually all mobiles know how to play MP3 files, no MP3 player knows how to phone.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Do not prevent there are enough reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to put the new Maxim Turbulenc album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to put it simply - MP3 music.
There are also categories depending on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for one reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty bearing earphones purchased for twenty crowns in the market.
There are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and texting, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, even serve navigation.
And if you take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can grill meat and no TV will take pictures, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The greater the number of functions you use, the lower the interval between two recharges.
And the reading of music is one of the most important energy goinfres.
There are few mobile phones that are able to read music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases, this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are much more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, be aware that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, make sure you get a second charger for the job - this is true even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable, as a result of a recharge, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
You can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to take it without a discount, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need, except for iPod, any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or by the judgment of the user.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a specific device, you are most interested in the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of ordering.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, it is enough for you any mobile reading MP3s.
Virtually all mobile devices are capable of doing so today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
Everyone gets to play the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will arrive until you will have exactly this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also read WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding operator’s web pages (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to acquire a musical mobile.
The supply of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to radio tubes quickly made.
The prices are also not the lowest.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you’ve forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheaper ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can have a very suitable walkman already.
But, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of output for regular listeners.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also provided with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Truly anyone who manages to ensure the ordering of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even if you take into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models basically only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones come out even with 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of control approaches that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the furthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunication Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher for us than for the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there was no more room for another operator, made choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a classical operator with his own network apparently no longer has much luck (for now, he would only find it difficult to find frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which, subsequently, the traditional operators also had to react.
However, even before the introduction of party disturbances such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those heard today in our home were heard in Britain.
Now, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
Moreover, we are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which owns, among other things, the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order for their operation to be effective, they actually need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators are profiled as low-cost carriers – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, Vodafone’s spokesman, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
All the more so as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of offering services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokesman for the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were, at any rate, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonica in the field of corporate customers, has not, for quite a long time, hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner the better.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility several times with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have succeeded in making progress in the negotiations,” said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by a total silence.
“At the moment, we don’t think there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared with other very specific ones.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press department of Telefonica O2, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project for the time being, which could serve as a basis."
She added: “It’s virtually ruled out that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate within such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Instead, Vodafone directs its attention to the fulfillment of requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructures.
This, in our opinion, means the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of making it easier for such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to understand each other like larrons at a fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by information accessible to the public from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
Now, today, the U:fon lends itself to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators as here, the indifference of the Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, it is not only the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously presented enough interest for classical operators," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Affairs of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Such a statement would not come as a surprise on the part of the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care, that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Foreign, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, putting pressure on the honest functioning of the market and on falling prices is apparently not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching chord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not reported any signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their market behaviour.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at all times.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are visibly acting in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Repealing responsibility for <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common shift in communications, through which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to pass the telecommunications law, recently adopted, an extension of the powers of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this very well, but their interests appear to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile phone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it’s about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specialized mobile phone services are offered for example by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic round consists of the fact that the company in front of the operator is a classic company client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you're talking about is happening, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions we would be considering and that could result in a termination of the collaboration with the company in question," said Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity will not be reached to those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned there can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, opposes such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible profits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is precisely what should seem strange in the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, there is another question at the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When We Are No Longer the Most Expensive Country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has resulted in a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, classical operators sometimes tried more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies involved in the developed countries, which were not defending the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up getting the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the manner of a hot potato, which is eliminated by transmitting it to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in their skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But don't throw away the handle after the cognac.
If the slide information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our house, the Czech mobile market may be moving.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain impassive in the face of rejection (to discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topol<0xC3><0xA1>nek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with chorus and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kate<0xC5><0x99>ina Kn<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD>nkov<0xC3><0xA1> and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremi<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0xA1> and Jaroslav Kr<0xC4><0x8D>ek are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek considers Czech national anthem as one of the most beautiful anthems.
As he had previously entrusted to <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> rzhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that both singers, as well as the chorus, have a good diction, so that one can understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech National Anthem will be celebrating its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j first reheard in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of the States) in Fidlova<0xC4><0x8D>ka (Kermesse des savetiers), a Czech original piece by Josef Kajet<0xC3><0xA1>n Tyl, accompanied by the music of Franti<0xC5><0xA1>ek <0xC5><0xA0>kroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet became naturally an integral part of the national anthem.
