Rats also have sensations.
A rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he experiences the same thing when he behaves the same way we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without which I or anyone else has until now been able to prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, one can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or generally of consciousness, we enter hard-to-work terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees, or attacks.
Humans behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a similar subjective experience.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make it difficult to transpose our subjective experience to that of animals.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and management and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to suppose that the human being differs even from the other primates.
Another significant feature could reside in the linguistic nature of man: since much of his existence is related to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness should not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, is neither allowed to be measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation causes us great problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their content, and this is exactly what happened during studies on the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does this mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a conscious brain of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the state of mind in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its sequences, such as the reactions of the body) captures living memory.
In this way, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluptuous nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than ourselves.
On the contrary, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities are born in the regions of the corporeal sensation of the Cortex and the brain stem, as well as Jaak Pankseep which, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
As this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could fully participate in transversal sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I can't contradict it, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in both Men and rats is probably as felt as it is in both cases: how could one check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees from danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my view, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Of course, the nervous comparison helps: rats and men have similar brain stems, but cockroaches don’t even have a brain.
But is the brain stem at the origin of sensations?
And even if one could prove it to Man, how could one prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is made on the nervous plane to the extent that the same is observed in rats and in humans.
Since I don’t explore language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I don’t know if they exist.
One might judge this as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly leaning against a wall.
I am, in fact, an emotional pragmatist.
