Talking in a Dormant
Some children talk during the night.
I do not refer to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk during their sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquy.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, there are more than one who speaks during the night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (pip in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very strong fevers, stressful or overexcited situations.
However, it is an unexplored phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a small quiet voice, with isolated words, whispers or vice versa with screams, tears, long speeches...
In the event that sleepiness becomes very frequent, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children and those who are struggling to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleepwalkers appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will no longer remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and so rests.
Remember that if he appears very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), don’t have the temptation to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because while sleeping, he's not conscious to be able to organize his thought.
Moreover, you will hear what he is saying, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so pay attention to how you will interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can ask him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
