The interview - Your blood has become safe
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public’s confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public outrage, the Government of Canada instituted in February 1994 a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not happen again.
While Judge Krever was delaying filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
In an effort to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” she said, before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94 percent of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, maintains in her mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when this is not known and that a serious illness can result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we can measure death.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
Now, a few years ago, it was shown beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: the nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow detecting directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
TANs have shortened the wet period, which extends between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, says the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
In this way, the risk of some donors being infected has been substantially reduced and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health,” says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant,” continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person, 18 years of age or older, who meets the eligibility criteria, can still donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
“With today’s life so frightful, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood,” Décary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These fabrics are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and are expected to pick up more than one thousand a year.
We should start offering it for transplants at the beginning of next year," said Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
“Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it,” as Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
