Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice President and Chief Executive Officer of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the sou in order to launch a “transparent public debate”.
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable money to prepare their defenses and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers backed by the mine’s almost bottomless pockets.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is in fact often to ruin the defenders in order to impose a friendly settlement that will bully the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is happening in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas rather than by a no-brainer.
It was therefore sufficient for the mine to open its books, its records and to establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the back of hand petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate at the same time while disregarding the views of that same public?
In the world of the vice president, it seems that this word refers only to fat-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of the mine.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilised exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a barrage of prosecution (because of the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a settlement in place of the authors of Black Canada).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in block, the right to citation of credible sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease the wealthy businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of repeated prosecution, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic environment, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms that limit this kind of abuse.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months is yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It provides, inter alia, for better control by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the return of committed public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, and a right to look at the salaries paid to the leaders of the bailed-out companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done in a way that protects the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis in Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos, and disruptions to Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” Republican Judd Gregg said.
Negotiations had taken a turn in the last few hours for fear of the effect of a new failure on investor mood.
The time limit given was the opening of the markets this morning.
Associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election proved rather favorable to the agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction that one is forced to reach that end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the one aimed at allowing homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of state-backed business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on U.S. television.
Asked on another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The big lines I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky, and unsold debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgages at risk (subprimes) before it spread to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and decomposes on a bank loan.
It was a group of Republican elected officials who had the first draft of the agreement, last week.
It is believed to have come out of this impasse since Democrats have accepted that some “toxic” assets of struggling companies are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the corner for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to take losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion to which an additional $100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be approved by another congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain shares in the relief companies that will be worth dividends to him in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the procedures for seizure of housing attached to the real estate loans concerned by the plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and severance payments paid to the leaders of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, voices continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that benefits taxpayers.”
Animator of a small group in Congress called "the caucus of the skeptics", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred prominent economics professors, including three Nobel Prizes, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully examine the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion (US16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had refused to acquire its competitor in full shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion U.S. dollars) in the US loan crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and 10 largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In exchange, a right to vote is recovered from the bank and from the influence.
It’s just something that savers and households now appreciate that times are uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed about to nationalize another bank tainted by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take back all of the ongoing loans from the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the UK bank’s branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
