The psychology of overexploitation: why are we spending more money?
When selling at auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have managed to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don’t want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that’s why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using sales at experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was playing the lotto, while the other group was taking part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (MRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction of which an essential element is the overhang of a third, the set under the brainstem, called striatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the part.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent reaction of striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
During these, three groups over-enhancing against one partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed on one victory, while on the other, on failure.
Thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the player team "against failure" were willing to make higher bets than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them only explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that patients with the hepatitis virus in Hungary are one hundred miles away, but only seven miles are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to the pathogens, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then a visible jaundice develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stool becomes clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Worldwide, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are unaware of the virus, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a surreptitious way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of a cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
