The smart car mimics the flight of the bourdon
What method would be better to develop technologies that are capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it were not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CETATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of starting, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a self-driving bio-inspired, BR23C-type self-driving system that it has equipped with bee qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own oval-shaped space, which in reality looks a lot like our protected hull - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the brand's research and development and technological public relations department at the exhibition.
The bee’s facetted eye plays a crucial role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the facet eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
The latter identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely in an instinctive way.
“If it wasn’t, the mini car robot wouldn’t be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the time being the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid the other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use rotary movement, acceleration as well as slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentration is greater, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a capacity of giga-bytes, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance, which Nissan estimates will make its entry into series-manufactured cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
