The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with the outside world, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost national here.
Political internationalisation really seems out of the question, or rather, it has little to say: the clear evidence is provided to us by the European Union, which, as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, fails to decide on any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and especially a credit condition: when we go through a difficult period, there are only states that have economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to get them back.
