The super glue to walk on the walls.
Win the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded there.
With an adhesive barely measuring 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called nano carbon tubes.
“The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a spaghetti stack,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that make it possible to ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "detachs easily from the wall", explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Engineering.
MARKER ON THE WALLS? – “This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Could be to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since nano carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could be related to aerospace engineering.
At the moment, no superheroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive formed from microfibers like hair, which self-cleans dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
