Farewell to old Paradiso cinema, the cities eliminate the historical rooms.
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image provided by the director Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates what is happening in the great Italian urban centers, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of consumption of mono-rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that we find inescapable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
It is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we have shared a bit of a path and so many emotions" observes the director of the premiere of the Nuovo cinéma Paradiso, the film that offers the film to Tornatore
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: over the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the rooms of the main cities that have paid the most: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is in the lead with 82 cinemas single rooms lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian operation has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room is closed in a city, these multiplexers are not necessarily available to all.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the state's previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 million and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year.
Let us note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to solve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the mono-room cinemas of historical centers and on the outskirts.
Among the planned regulations, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," notes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by putting in place other measures.
