When energy is born from waves, now the big ones launch.
This is an unmeasured deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s largest energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that colossals like Chevron have laid eyes on, and are now trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of oil declined, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore operating systems.
This amount would be twice as much as that produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colises at the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, a real revolutionary step would have been said.
Two years from now, more and more candidates among these companies, always devoted to traditional energy, are betting on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” said a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant, the Wall Street Journal, and it assesses the possibilities of cooperating with us.
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit, which is intended by the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially if one considers that exactly in Alaska, the U.S. continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which traverse the path of energy coming from the sea, and the sums invested so far, although their details are not known, according to observers, an increasing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, on the part of the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create a major problem in the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the mud up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure rotates a turbine which, in turn, feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through cables under sea.
At the moment, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could serve a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping center and a parking lot using six marine turbines of the East River of New York.
The movement of water during tides, rotates the turbine blades, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw on energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Research of Electric Energy, now deserves the potential of tides.
Although this is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
